{
    "level": "A2",
    "intro": "In this topic, you will learn <strong>what the passive voice is</strong>, how it differs from the active voice, and in what cases it is used.",
    "rules": [
        {
            "label": "Active",
            "color": "emerald",
            "text": "<strong>Active state</strong> — the subject performs an action:",
            "example": "Tom writes a letter."
        },
        {
            "label": "Passive",
            "color": "blue",
            "text": "<strong>Passive state</strong> — the subject receives an action:",
            "example": "A letter is written by Tom."
        },
        {
            "label": "When?",
            "color": "rose",
            "text": "When the performer is <strong>unknown, unimportant</strong> or obvious:",
            "example": "The window was broken."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "1. What are Active and Passive?",
    "intro": "In English, a sentence can be in two states:",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "Active Voice",
            "title": "Active",
            "subtitle": "The subject performs the action. Focus on the performer."
        },
        {
            "label": "Passive Voice",
            "title": "Passive",
            "subtitle": "The subject gains an action. Focus on action or result."
        },
        {
            "label": "Transformation",
            "title": "Object → Subject",
            "subtitle": "The object of the active sentence becomes the subject in the passive."
        },
        {
            "label": "Agent",
            "title": "Performer (by)",
            "subtitle": "You can specify the artist through \"by\", but it is often omitted."
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "2. Comparison of Active vs Passive",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "Active Voice",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "The subject <strong>performs</strong> an action. Structure: <strong>Subject + Verb + Object</strong>",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "Tom writes a letter.",
                    "ua": "Tom writes a letter."
                },
                {
                    "en": "She cleaned the room.",
                    "ua": "She cleaned the room."
                },
                {
                    "en": "They build houses.",
                    "ua": "They build houses."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "Passive Voice",
            "color": "blue",
            "description": "The subject <strong>gets</strong> the action. Structure: <strong>Subject + be + V3 (+ by agent)</strong>",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "A letter is written by Tom.",
                    "ua": "A letter is written by Tom."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The room was cleaned.",
                    "ua": "The room was cleaned."
                },
                {
                    "en": "Houses are built here.",
                    "ua": "Houses are built here."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "3. When to use Passive Voice?",
    "sections": [
        {
            "label": "1. The performer is unknown",
            "color": "emerald",
            "description": "We don't know who performed the action:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "My car was stolen.",
                    "ua": "My car was stolen."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The window was broken.",
                    "ua": "The window was broken."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "2. The performer is unimportant",
            "color": "sky",
            "description": "We don't care who performs the action. An important result:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "English is spoken here.",
                    "ua": "English is spoken here."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The building was constructed in 1990.",
                    "ua": "The building was constructed in 1990."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "3. The executor is obvious",
            "color": "amber",
            "description": "It is clear who performs the action, so we do not name him:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "He was arrested.",
                    "ua": "He was arrested."
                },
                {
                    "en": "The letter was delivered.",
                    "ua": "The letter was delivered."
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "label": "4. Formal/scientific style",
            "color": "rose",
            "description": "In scientific texts and official documents, the passive voice sounds more objective:",
            "examples": [
                {
                    "en": "The experiment was conducted.",
                    "ua": "The experiment was conducted."
                },
                {
                    "en": "It is believed that...",
                    "ua": "It is believed that..."
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
}

{
    "title": "4. Active → Passive transformation",
    "intro": "How to change a sentence from active to passive:",
    "rows": [
        {
            "en": "Active: Tom writes a letter.",
            "ua": "Active: Tom writes a letter.",
            "note": "→ Passive: A letter is written by Tom."
        },
        {
            "en": "Active: She cleaned the room.",
            "ua": "Active: She cleaned the room.",
            "note": "→ Passive: The room was cleaned (by her)."
        },
        {
            "en": "Active: They build houses.",
            "ua": "Active: They build houses.",
            "note": "→ Passive: Houses are built."
        }
    ],
    "warning": "📌 The <strong>Object</strong> of an active sentence becomes the <strong>Subject</strong> of a passive one!"
}

{
    "title": "5. Short summary",
    "items": [
        "<strong>Active Voice</strong>: the subject performs the action → Tom writes a letter.",
        "<strong>Passive Voice</strong>: the subject receives the action → A letter is written.",
        "<strong>Object → Subject</strong>: the object of the active sentence becomes the subject of the passive.",
        "<strong>When to use</strong>: artist unknown, unimportant, obvious, or for a formal style.",
        "<strong>Agent (by)</strong>: Indicates the artist, but is often omitted."
    ]
}

{
    "title": "Other pages from the basics of the passive voice",
    "items": [
        {
            "label": "What is Passive Voice? (current)",
            "current": true
        },
        {
            "label": "Form: be + V3 (Past Participle)",
            "current": false
        },
        {
            "label": "Present Simple Passive",
            "current": false
        },
        {
            "label": "Past Simple Passive",
            "current": false
        }
    ]
}
